---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import { localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import DurableTaskKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/DurableTaskKeystone.astro";
import AttemptContinueFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/AttemptContinueFlow.astro";
import DurableBoundaryFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/DurableBoundaryFlow.astro";
import BudgetLayersFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/BudgetLayersFlow.astro";
import ColdStartResumeFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ColdStartResumeFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="04" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      Work that does not fit an interactive Turn needs its own task identity and progress that can
      survive process boundaries. Headless Durable Task Loop upgrades “one chat” into “a task that can
      continue” — without rewriting the §01–§03 Runtime; it wraps execution in a durable envelope. Key
      line:
      <strong>A task is longer than a turn; durability begins by giving the task its own log.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§04 · Scene"
    title="Start from a task that cannot finish in one round"
    lede="Session chat alone cannot answer Attempt, budget, park, or workspace ownership."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the task is: read a large codebase, migrate an old API, fix the build step by step, and
      pause at high-risk permissions for confirmation. It may: do inventory only on the first round;
      end a Run on a tool-step cap while the task is unfinished; need a second execution that knows
      which files were checked and which todos are open; park waiting for approval; resume hours later;
      and survive a process restart that wiped in-memory loop counters and the active backend.
    </p>
    <p>
      Turn expresses one Q&amp;A; Run expresses one concrete execution; the RuntimeEvent ledger can
      replay model and tool experience — the fact layer already locked in §01–§03. A long task still
      must answer another set of questions: stable goal id, attempt count, remaining budget, effective
      progress, running vs waiting for approval, what to inherit next, whether the workspace is still
      the one left behind, and who may take the next step.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Headless’s real problem is how to turn an open goal across Attempts, parks, and even process
      restarts into a projectable Task Event history — not how to pretend one Invocation can live
      forever.
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§04 · Keystone"
    title="TaskRun is a durable envelope outside the Runtime"
    lede="Headless does not rewrite Agent Runtime; it organizes Runtime execution into a long Task lifecycle."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · TaskRun wraps bounded Attempts; cross-Attempt facts enter the Task Event Log and project as next-work view."
      alt="TaskRun envelope with Attempt 1/2, Task Event Log, dashed TaskRun Projection; invariant: a task is longer than a turn."
    >
      <DurableTaskKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>TaskRun</strong> — who owns the long goal from start to terminal (across Attempts)</li>
      <li><strong>Attempt</strong> — one progress slice with budget boundaries</li>
      <li><strong>Turn</strong> — one input/reply handed to the Agent</li>
      <li><strong>Run / Invocation</strong> — start/end of one model+tool loop</li>
    </ul>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Task projection">TaskRunProjection(t) = Project(TaskEvents[0..t])

Long task progress
  = sequence of bounded Attempts
  + durable Task Events between them
  + explicitly selected continuation state</pre>
    <p>
      A projection is not a second Task truth that can be edited on its own. CLI inspect, resume
      planning, prompt replay, and export should all derive from Task Events — the same discipline as
      §01 (“state is a function of the log”) and §03 (“a checkpoint is a projection”), with the long-task
      control plane as the consumer.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="session"
    label="§04 · Identity"
    title="Why Session is still not a TaskRun"
    lede="Dialogue ownership and durable orchestration must not contaminate each other."
  >
    <p>
      A Session can span many Turns and keep model history, but mainly answers “who owns this
      conversation.” A TaskRun must also express Attempt counts and outcomes, loop budget,
      permission/budget parks, cross-Attempt progress/evidence, workspace lease,
      continue/retry/stop/abort, and the effective task policy. Ordinary interactive chat should not
      be forced to carry these control fields; different Attempts may currently create different
      Sessions / AgentRuns. Reference direction: Task Events store <code>sessionId</code> /
      <code>agentRunId</code>; the Session header is not the TaskRun truth.
    </p>
    <p>
      Stuff Task control fields into Session and interactive chat inherits unattended semantics; treat
      the Session header as Task truth and park / budget / multi-Attempt cannot honestly rebuild after
      restart. Keep the two identities separate and cross-link with refs.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside</p>
      <p>
        Durable Task Loop architecture chapter land:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/773")}`}>maka:pr:773</a>
        (docs: add durable task loop architecture chapter). Related Task ledger lifecycle:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/567")}`}>maka:pr:567</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="durable"
    label="§04 · Current"
    title="What is actually durable"
    lede="Durable control-plane facts ≠ the whole execution world is checkpointed."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · TaskRun ledger owns control-plane facts; workspace / live stream / auto-takeover remain Target gaps."
      alt="Left column Current ledger owns; right column Not guaranteed by ledger alone."
    >
      <DurableBoundaryFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>TaskRunStore</code> appends TaskEvents as JSONL;
      <code>projectTaskRun()</code> projects status, Attempts, progress, evidence, permission, parked
      state, and Runtime refs from the start. Explicitly durable today: TaskRun identity, appended
      Task Events, recorded Attempt / progress / decision / permission / lifecycle, and refs to
      Session, AgentRun, RuntimeEvents, and artifacts.
    </p>
    <p>
      Not guaranteed by the TaskRun ledger alone: current bytes of a temporary workspace, an in-flight
      provider stream, live tool process handles, in-memory backends / abort controllers, whether an
      external executor still holds the same workspace, or whether a scheduler auto-takes over after
      restart.
    </p>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        Current: TaskRun ledger and Attempt wrapping are shipped. Target: a unified cross-process
        safe-takeover checkpoint protocol (workspace, in-flight Invocation, scheduler ownership) —
        teaching must label this explicitly; do not pretend it is already guaranteed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="attempt"
    label="§04 · Attempt"
    title="An Attempt is a progress slice, not a synonym for failure"
    lede="Outer policy decides continue / retry / stop / abort — not resurrecting an immortal Invocation."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Attempt ends → append TaskEvent → policy gate → project next-work; continue = new Attempt."
      alt="Five steps: runTaskOnce, Attempt ends, Append TaskEvt, Policy gate, Next view."
    >
      <AttemptContinueFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Layered budgets: maxAttempts · maxRuntimeSteps · park/stop/abort — no infinite continue."
      alt="Three columns: maxAttempts, maxRuntimeSteps, policy gates."
    >
      <BudgetLayersFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      An Attempt may end on normal stop, execution failure, incomplete information, permission block,
      budget exhaustion, cancel, or abort. <code>AutonomousAgentLoop</code> creates a new Attempt on
      each <code>runTaskOnce()</code> — it does not resume from an old RuntimeRunner instruction
      pointer, nor revive an exited tool process. Layered budgets (e.g. <code>maxAttempts</code> /
      <code>maxRuntimeSteps</code>) give unattended loops a provable boundary: there is no infinite
      license to “continue until done.” Even if a custom policy asks to continue,
      <code>enforceCaps()</code> reapplies the hard limits.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="continue"
    label="§04 · Continuation"
    title="“Continue” is at least three paths — not one resume"
    lede="Autonomous continue, parked CLI resume, and cold-start ledger reload — different semantics, explicit events."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Three continuations: autonomous continue/retry · parked needs_approval · cold-start ledger reload; unified resume stays Target."
      alt="Four columns: Autonomous continue, Parked resume, Cold start reload, Target unified resume gap."
    >
      <ColdStartResumeFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        <strong>Autonomous continue / retry</strong> — call <code>runTaskOnce()</code> again;
        heavy-task state can project from Task Events into a new instruction; optionally splice prior
        Attempt RuntimeEvents into the next Runtime context. Still a new Attempt — not
        instruction-level resume.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Parked permission CLI resume</strong> — when intervention is <code>park</code>, an
        Inbox / <code>needs_approval</code> forms; current <code>task resume</code> mainly serves this
        path: resolve inbox, open a new Attempt, append grant facts to the Task Event Log.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Cold start</strong> — after process restart, reload JSONL and
        <code>projectTaskRun()</code>; attempt / step counts must not reset because a new process
        started. What recovers is control-plane truth — not live tool handles or automatic scheduler
        takeover.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Explicit continuation must leave Task Events; an in-process loop counter alone is not enough.
      Collapsing the three into one “resume” button smuggles semantics between park and crash, and
      dresses Target’s unified takeover protocol as Current.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="failure"
    label="§04 · Failure"
    title="Stop on an explainable boundary — do not pretend you can still continue"
    lede="Fail closed on budgets and ownership; do not invent a live world from a ledger alone."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        Budget / hard cap hit → stop the unattended loop; do not bypass
        <code>enforceCaps()</code> with “one more try.”
      </li>
      <li>
        Permission fail-closed or park → no side effects without a grant; parked resume must record
        grant facts.
      </li>
      <li>
        After restart, missing workspace / executor ownership evidence → restore control-plane
        projection only; do not claim safe live-world takeover.
      </li>
      <li>
        Prior Attempt RuntimeEvents may optionally replay into context, but must not pretend the tool
        process is still running.
      </li>
      <li>
        Custom policy asks to continue while hard caps are exhausted → caps win over narrative.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Hybrid teaching depth</p>
      <p>
        This chapter is thickened under the Hybrid decision: as the Runtime→durable-task bridge, its
        narrative and continuation figure approach §01–§03 density. §05–§06 stay lean and
        checklist-complete; finer evolution detail lives in <code>/history</code> asides.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Keystone + durable boundary + Attempt continue + budgets + three continuations / cold start</li>
      <li>
        Aside: <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/773")}`}>maka:pr:773</a>
      </li>
      <li>Current ledger vs Target cross-process takeover gaps labeled</li>
      <li>Hybrid: §04 fuller; §05–§06 lean; checklist hard gate met (zh+en same ship)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

